	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64839657"><p>Daily driving isn't the issue.  If I want to go to New York (which is 3 hours away) I don't want to have to plan out my route so I can find a charging station.  Nor do I want to sit around for half an hour waiting for my car to charge which, for a trip like that, would be at least twice.</p><p>When I go on vacation I drive. If I'm in some small town in the middle of Kansas, do you think I'm going to find a charging station?</p><p>These are not "edge" cases. These are real life considerations which have to be taken into account.  Until charging stations are more ubiquitous AND do not require a "smart" phone to operate, EVs will be relegated to daily driving or pre-planned routes with no option for sightseeing.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64839657">
